re typical of cases throughout the United States. The children represent a range of ages and ethnic and socio-economic backgrounds. The cases illustrate a variety of placement issues including sexual abuse, abandonment, adoption, and visitation conflicts. In each case, the authors attempt to demonstrate that the least harmful decision-making is based on sound principles of child development: the child’s need for continuity of affectionate relationships and his or her need to feel wanted by at least one responsible adult. The book, illustrating useful ways of resolving child-placement conflicts, will be an essential guide and resource for all who work in this complex field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAbused childrenxFamily relationshipszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aAdoptionzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aChild developmentzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aFoster childrenxFamily relationshipszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aFoster home carezUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSELF-HELP / Abuse.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311053801440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015761140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300157611423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300157611/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles